Many recent studies~\cite{tang2019joint,yi2019citytraffic} use graph embeddings or GNN to model the spatio-temporal dependencies in data for network-wide traffic state estimation. Researchers further combine temporal GCN with variational autoencoder and generative adversarial network to impute network-wide traffic state~\cite{qin2021network}. However, most of these methods assume the connectivity between road segments is static, whereas the connectivity changes dynamically with traffic signals in the real world. Moreover, all the graph-based methods do not explicitly consider the flow transition between road segments in their model. As a result, the model would likely infer a volume for a road segment when the nearby road segments do not hold that volume in the past.


